'''{{ill|Kin-gū|ja|金武宮|12=draft}}''' (金武宮, Kin-gū) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Kin Town]], [[Kunigami District]], [[Okinawa Prefecture]], Japan. It is one of the [[Ryukyu Eight Shrines]] and was an unranked shrine in the [[Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Meiji period]].

== Deities ==
; Kumano Gongen
* [[Izanami-no-Mikoto]]
* [[Hayatama-no-Mikoto]]
* [[Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto]]

== History ==
The exact origin of the shrine is unknown. According to ''Shrines of Okinawa'', no shrine buildings were constructed since its founding<ref>''Shrines of Okinawa'', 2000, p. 32.</ref>.

The ''[[Records of the Ryukyu Kingdom]]'' Volume 11, section on Kinpusan Kannon-ji, contains the "Kimpusan Fudarakuin Kannon-ji Temple Origin," which mentions that the monk [[Nisshu (Shingon)|Nisshu Shonin]], who traveled in search of Mount Fudaraku, founded the temple during the reign of King Shō Sei. He identified the cave at this location as a sacred site and built the shrine, enshrining three deities he carved himself.

According to ''Research on Ryukyu Religious History'', the stalactite cave is considered the [[Shintai|main body]] of the shrine. Therefore, it is believed that Nisshu Shonin, who established Kannon-ji Temple, also founded this shrine. This would date the shrine's founding to between 1527 and 1555, the reign of King Shō Sei.

Under the "official shrine system," it was designated one of the Ryukyu Eight Shrines. As the shrine did not have a resident priest and was managed by the abbot of Kannon-ji Temple, it did not receive financial support from the royal government<ref name="shukyoushi5-2-3">''Research on Ryukyu Religious History'', Vol. 5, Chapter 2, Section 3, 1965.</ref>.

After the {{ill|Invasion of Ryukyu|8=en|10=ja|11=琉球侵攻|12=draft}} in 1609, shrines of the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} lineage began to receive more favorable treatment. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000}} For example, until the 16th century, prayers at the royal court were performed by Noro organizations led by {{ill|Kikoe-ōgimi|8=en|10=ja|11=聞得大君|12=draft}} and Zen temples, but after the invasion of the Satsuma domain, prayers for bountiful harvests were carried out by Noro organizations, prayers for the good health of the royal family and the peace of the nation were carried out by {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} shrines such as Naminoue-gu and Futenma-gu, and royal funerals and ancestral memorial services were carried out by Zen temples. In addition, in {{ill|1625|8=en|10=ja|11=尚豊王|12=draft}}, it became customary to visit the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} shrines in addition to the Zen temples and Chinese shrines as a {{ill|New|8=en|10=ja|11=尚賢王|12=draft}} Year's event, and in 1644, the king's visit to Futenma-gu Shrine (Hutinma-mee) became a regular event, attracting the reverence of ordinary people as well. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000}} In 1671, the head priest of Gokoku-ji Temple, Yorimichi, requested {{ill|Shō Shōken|8=en|10=ja|11=羽地朝秀|12=draft}} to convert the Rinzai sect temples Manju-ji Temple (Sueyoshi-gu Shrine), Jin'o-ji Temple (Shikina-gu Shrine), and Seigen-ji Temple (Ameku-gu Shrine) to Shingon Buddhism. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000}} {{Sfn|新垣裕之|2021}} It is believed that through these events, the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} shrines became {{ill|kanpei-sha|8=en|10=ja|11=官幣社|12=draft}}, and {{ill|the Eight Ryukyu Shrines|8=en|10=ja|11=琉球八社|12=draft}} were established. {{Sfn|鳥越憲三郎|1965}} {{Sfn|加治順人|2000}} {{Sfn|新垣裕之|2021}} {{Refn|The Ryukyu Eight Shrines are {{ill|Naminoue Shrine|ja|波上宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Oki-no-gū‎|ja|沖宮|1=Oki-no-gū‎|12=draft}}, {{ill|Asato-Hachimangū‎|ja|八幡宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shikina-gū|ja|識名宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sueyoshi-gū|ja|末吉宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ameku-gū|ja|天久宮|12=draft}}, {{ill|Futemma-gū|ja|普天満宮|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kin-gū|ja|金武宮|12=draft}}. All of them belong to the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} lineage. However, since Kin-gū did not have a shrine building or priests and did not receive maintenance funds from the royal government, there is a theory that the other seven shrines are considered kanpei-sha{{sfn|鳥越憲三郎|1965|pp=589-596}}{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=67-70}}{{sfn|新垣裕之|2021|pp=70-73}}。Additionally, among the seven shrines listed as major shrines in the "Ryukyu Shinto Record," {{ill|Chojugu Shrine|ja|長寿宮|12=draft}} (later {{ill|Ukishima Shrine|ja|浮島神社|12=draft}}) and {{ill|Choraku-ji Tenmangū|ja|長楽寺天満宮|sn|天満宮|12=draft}}, which are not of the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家}} lineage, are excluded from the kanpei-sha.{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=70-73}}。|group=注釈}} {{Refn|In mainland Japan, many {{ill|kanpei-sha|ja|官幣社|12=draft}} shrines are associated with the imperial family or powerful clans through blood relations or ancestral ties. However, in Ryukyu, which had an imported religion, there are no such traditions. It is also characteristic that the establishment tales of the Ryukyu Eight Shrines often involve some kind of spiritual phenomenon.{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=70-73}}。|group=注釈}}

In the [[Meiji period]], with the [[Ryukyu Disposition]] and the establishment of Okinawa Prefecture, the Meiji government aimed to integrate the Ryukyu people under Japanese state religion by transforming or suppressing native Ryukyu religious practices<ref name="shukyoushi5-1">''Research on Ryukyu Religious History'', Vol. 5, Chapter 1, 1965.</ref>. Despite plans to classify the shrine as a village shrine, it remained unranked due to its lack of parishioner organization and inadequate facilities. Efforts were made to gradually improve the shrine for future reclassification as a village shrine<ref name="shukyoushi5-4-2">''Research on Ryukyu Religious History'', Vol. 5, Chapter 4, Section 2, 1965.</ref>.

In 1939, as part of Okinawa Prefecture's revitalization project, a restoration plan for the Ryukyu Eight Shrines was implemented. At that time, the shrine was a simple earthenware structure, 1.5 shaku (about 45 cm) wide and 2 shaku (about 60 cm) deep, with a ridge height of 2.5 shaku (about 76 cm)<ref name="shukyoushi5-5-1">''Research on Ryukyu Religious History'', Vol. 5, Chapter 5, Section 1, 1965.</ref>. The current shrine is depicted in the template image.

